'''Hatfield Marine Science Center''' (HMSC) is a [[marine science]] research and education center next to [[Yaquina Bay]] of the [[Pacific Ocean]] in the [[U.S. state]] of [[Oregon]]. It is operated by [[Oregon State University]] (OSU) in cooperation with five state and federal agencies co-located on site. Named after [[Mark Hatfield]], a former [[U.S. Senate|U.S. Senator]] from Oregon,<ref>{{cite web|title=A Message from Senator Hatfield |url=http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/friends/hatfield.html |publisher=Friends of the Hatfield Marine Sciences Center, Oregon State University |year = 2003 |accessdate=January 5, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720025424/http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/friends/hatfield.html |archivedate=July 20, 2011 |df= }}</ref> the HMSC occupies a {{convert|49|acre|ha|adj=on}} site in [[Newport, Oregon|Newport]].<ref name ="Strategic Plan">{{cite web|title = Hatfield Marine Science Center: Strategic Plan |url = http://ir.library.oregonstate.edu/xmlui/bitstream/handle/1957/5036/HMSCStratPln1206.pdf;jsessionid=17AF2C469B10D97379E0F699DE314A81?sequence=1|publisher = Oregon State University|date = December 2006|format = PDF|page = 4|accessdate = January 3, 2011}}</ref> The Hatfield Marine Science Center campus is the future site of the new Oregon State University Marine Studies Initiative building, with a proposed year-round undergraduate student body of 500 students.
==Visitor Center== Opened in 1965, the Hatfield Marine Science Visitor Center is the public education wing of the HMSC. The visitor center's exhibits focus on marine species, marine research, and the coastal environment.<ref>{{cite web|title=Hatfield Marine Science Center Visitor Center: About Us |url=http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/visit/about |publisher=Oregon State University |accessdate=January 3, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110306170636/http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/visit/about |archivedate=March 6, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Live marine animals on display include a [[Enteroctopus dofleini|Giant Pacific Octopus]].<ref name="Exhibits and Events">{{cite web|title=Exhibits and Events |publisher=Oregon State University |year=2011 |url=http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/exhibits-and-events |accessdate=January 4, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720025007/http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/exhibits-and-events |archivedate=July 20, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Other exhibits focus on weather, [[tsunami]], commercial fishing, ocean resource management, microscopic sea life, and [[tide pool|tide-pool]] creatures and habitats.<ref name = "Exhibits and Events"/> The visitor center offers public programs and tours and is open year-round.<ref name="Visit">{{cite web|title=Visit |publisher=Oregon State University |date=2011 |url=http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/visit |accessdate=January 4, 2011 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110720024902/http://hmsc.oregonstate.edu/visitor/visit |archivedate=July 20, 2011 |df= }}</ref> Admission is by donation.<ref name = "Visit"/>
==Employees== More than 300 people work at the HMSC, including OSU faculty, graduate students, researchers, and staff from agencies including [[Oregon Department of Fish and Wildlife]], [[US Fish and Wildlife Service]], [[US Environmental Protection Agency]], [[US Department of Agriculture]], and the [[National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration]] (NOAA).<ref name ="Woods Hole">{{cite news|last = Killen |first = John|title = Woods Hole of the West? That's what Newport hopes to become|publisher = Oregon Live LLC| url=http://www.oregonlive.com/news/index.ssf/2009/09/woods_hole_of_the_west_thats_w.html |date = September 5, 2009|accessdate = January 4, 2011}}</ref> NOAA employees at the HMSC are affiliated with the Alaska Fisheries Science Center,<ref>{{cite web|title = Alaska Fisheries Science Center: Fisheries Behavioral Ecology Program|url = http://www.afsc.noaa.gov/race/behavioral/default.php|publisher = National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration|date = March 27, 2009|accessdate = January 3, 2011}}</ref> Northwest Fisheries Science Center, or the [[Pacific Marine Environmental Laboratory]], all of which are headquartered in [[Seattle, Washington]], though NOAA itself is now located in Newport. The HMSC (and the Seafood Research & Education Center in [[Astoria, Oregon|Astoria]]) are home to the Coastal Oregon Marine Experiment Station (COMES),<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.coas.oregonstate.edu/marineportal/comes.html | archive-url = https://archive.is/20120801053211/http://www.coas.oregonstate.edu/marineportal/comes.html | dead-url = yes | archive-date = August 1, 2012 | title = Coastal Oregon Marine Experiment Station (COMES) | publisher = Oregon State University | year = 2005 | accessdate = May 2, 2008 }}</ref> the largest of 12 branch [[agricultural research station]]s in Oregon.
The OSU College of Oceanic and Atmospheric Sciences operates the [[RV Wecoma|Research Vessel ''Wecoma'']] which has its home port adjacent to the center.<ref>{{cite web|title = R/V Wecoma|url = http://www.shipops.oregonstate.edu/ops/wecoma/|publisher = Oregon State University|accessdate = January 4, 2011|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101229082639/http://www.shipops.oregonstate.edu/ops/wecoma/|archivedate = December 29, 2010|df = }}</ref> The college also operates the Research Vessel ''Elakha'' (Sea Otter) out of Newport.<ref>{{cite web|title = R/V Elakha|url = http://www.shipops.oregonstate.edu/ops/elakha/|publisher = Oregon State University|accessdate = January 4, 2011|deadurl = yes|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20101203061551/http://www.shipops.oregonstate.edu/ops/elakha/|archivedate = December 3, 2010|df = }}</ref>
