{{italic title}}
[[File:MainstreamsOfModernArt.jpg|thumb|First edition (publ. [[Simon & Schuster]])<br>Cover art:<br>[[Pablo Picasso]], ''[[Girl before a Mirror]]'', 1932<br>[[Thomas Eakins]], ''[[Miss Amelia Van Buren]]'', 1891]]
'''''Mainstreams of Modern Art: David to Picasso''''' (1959) is a reference book by [[John Canaday]].  It comprehensively covers [[modern art]] from the start of [[Romanticism]] in the 18th century to [[Cubism]] and [[Abstract art]] in the early 20th century.  ''Mainstreams'' enjoyed wide commercial and critical success, and was awarded the 1959 [[Athenaeum Literary Award]].<ref>[http://www.philaathenaeum.org/literary.html Literary Award Winners], The Athenæum of Philadelphia</ref>

It also contains a ten-page appendix "Notes on Modern Architecture", the final five pages of which are devoted to criticism of [[Frank Lloyd Wright]], whose design Canaday states "have failed disastrously."  But in the same sentence, he also praised Wright's buildings as "some of the most beautiful structures of the century bearing his name." This, combined with Canaday's other outspoken views, led a group of artists, collectors, and academics to write a letter to the ''[[New York Times]]'' in protest.<ref>[http://www.lib.duke.edu/lilly/artlibry/dah/canadayj.htm John Canaday], Duke University Libraries</ref>

A revised edition was published shortly before Canaday's death in 1985, and is still required reading at the university level in the United States<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.emich.edu/coe/NCATE2003/Docs/G-28/selectedsyllabi/adv/ART506.html |title=Bibliography |accessdate=2006-02-24 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031120102338/http://www.emich.edu/coe/NCATE2003/Docs/G-28/selectedsyllabi/adv/ART506.html |archivedate=November 20, 2003 |df= }}, ''ART 506: Art for the Talented and Gifted'', Eastern Michigan University (Retrieved on 13 March 2005)</ref> and worldwide.<ref>[http://www.uniraj.ernet.in/syllabi/B.V.A./BVA.html Required texts] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060111065259/http://www.uniraj.ernet.in/syllabi/B.V.A./BVA.html |date=2006-01-11 }}, ''Western Modern Art'', University of Rajasthan, Jaipur</ref>

==Editions==
